01","1100":"1100","about 1101":"circa 1101","about 1124":"circa 1124","1150":"1150","1182":"1182","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England"},"en":{"about 1101–":"about 1101–Deceased","1100–Male":"1100–Deceased","1124–1182":"1124–1182","1101–Female":"1101–Deceased","1106":"1106","1215":"1215","1124":"1124","1101":"1101","1100":"1100","about 1101":"about 1101","about 1124":"about 1124","1150":"1150","1182":"1182","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Raleigh","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Raleigh (House) in Pilton (Devon), recorded as <i>Radeleia</i> in 1086 and <i>Rawlegh</i> in 1535. The placename probably derives from Old English <i>rǣge</i> ‘roe deer’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","Irish: variant of   Riley  .","History: The English explorer Sir Walter Raleigh (1554–1618) was born in Hayes Barton, Devon, into a family of Devon gentry. He was related to most of the West Country's important families, including that of Sir Francis Drake. His half-brother was the explorer Sir Humphrey Gilbert. In 1578 Raleigh was granted a patent to explore and colonize “unknown lands” in America. In the 1580s he was granted extensive estates in Munster (Ireland), in reward for his suppression of the Desmond Rebellions."],"variants":[{"name":"Raley","meanings":["English: variant of   Raleigh  ."]},{"name":"Rawleigh","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Orlo.","English: variant of   Raleigh  , reflecting a common pronunciation."]},{"name":"Riley","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): habitational name chiefly from High Ryley in Accrington (Lancashire) and Riley in Kirkburton, which was in the manor of Wakefield (Yorkshire). In some cases the name may derive from Riley Farm in Eyam (Derbyshire), Royley in Royton (Lancashire), or Rylah in Scarcliffe (Derbyshire). The placenames all come from Old English <i>rȳge</i> ‘rye’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","Irish: from <b>Ó Raghailligh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Raghailleach</i>’, Old Irish <i>Roghallach</i>. This is the name of a chieftain family in Cavan, related to the O'Rourkes. In Anglicized form it has also been confused with <b>Ó Raithile</b> found in Munster, usually Anglicized as <b>O'Rahilly</b> or   Rahilly  . See   O'Reilly  ."]}]},{"name":"Cecily","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular English form of   Cecilia ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cecilie","meanings":["Medieval vernacular English form of   Cecilia ."]},{"name":"Cicely","meanings":["Variant of   Cecily .  This was a common form of the name in the Middle Ages, and in the 20th century was well known as the name of the British actress and singer  Cicely Courtneidge  (  1893–1980 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705185,"age":5,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705187,"age":114,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Cecily de Raleigh was born about 1101, in Essex, England. She married William 3rd baron d'abrancis in 1150. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1101–":"umbes 1101–Surnud","1100–Male":"1100–Surnud","1124–1182":"1124–1182","1101–Female":"1101–Surnud","1106":"1106","1215":"1215","1124":"1124","1101":"1101","1100":"1100","about 1101":"umbes 1101","about 1124":"umbes 1124","1150":"1150","1182":"1182","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England"},"fi":{"about 1101–":"noin 1101–Kuollut","1100–Male":"1100–Kuollut","1124–1182":"1124–1182","1101–Female":"1101–Kuollut","1106":"1106","1215":"1215","1124":"1124","1101":"1101","1100":"1100","about 1101":"noin 1101","about 1124":"noin 1124","1150":"1150","1182":"1182","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England"},"fr":{"about 1101–":"environ 1101–Décédée","1100–Male":"1100–Décédé","1124–1182":"1124–1182","1101–Female":"1101–Décédée","1106":"1106","1215":"1215","1124":"1124","1101":"1101","1100":"1100","about 1101":"environ 1101","about 1124":"environ 1124","1150":"1150","1182":"1182","London, Middlesex, England":"Londres, Middlesex, Angleterre","Essex, England":"Essex, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Cecily de Raleigh est née environ 1101, à Essex, Angleterre. Elle a épousé William 3rd baron d'abrancis en 1150. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille."